description:
## Severity
Major

## Dimension
Concurrency / Performance

## Location
src/tools/worktree.rs:25-46 (git_with_timeout polling loop)

## Violation
```rust
loop {
    match child.try_wait() {
        Ok(Some(_)) => return child.wait_with_output()...,
        Ok(None) => {
            if Instant::now() >= deadline { ... }
            std::thread::sleep(Duration::from_millis(100));
        }
        Err(e) => return Err(...),
    }
}
```

`std::thread::sleep` on a sync function called from a tokio runtime blocks the OS thread for 100ms per iteration. For a 5-second git command that's 50 wasted thread-block cycles. tools::cron.rs is also called from the same dispatcher. Under concurrent agent sessions the tokio worker pool is saturated by polling sleepers. Additionally, busy-polling adds up to 100ms of latency on EVERY git command even when git would have exited in 1ms.

## Mandated refactor
Replace the polling loop with one of:
1. `wait_timeout::ChildExt::wait_timeout(deadline_remaining)` from the wait_timeout crate (POSIX-safe, no polling).
2. If keeping the polling approach: lift the function to async, use `tokio::process::Child` + `tokio::time::timeout` so the wait is non-blocking. The dispatcher that called this function is async-served anyway.
3. Backoff polling (10ms → 20ms → 50ms → 100ms) reduces tail latency for fast commands.

